---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: [
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What is rsync used for?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'rsync is used to copy and synchronize files efficiently between local paths or remote systems over SSH.'
      }
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What does rsync -a do?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'The -a flag enables archive mode, preserving permissions, timestamps, symlinks, and recursive directory copying.'
      }
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Should I test rsync with dry-run first?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Yes. Use --dry-run before real sync jobs, especially with --delete, to review exactly what will change.'
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<BaseLayout title="Rsync Command Builder" description="Generate reliable rsync commands for Linux file sync and backup workflows.">
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="muted">Linux Dork Tools</p>
    <h1>Rsync Command Builder</h1>
    <p>Build sync commands with useful presets like archive, delete, and dry-run.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="card prose">
    <h2>Build safer Linux file sync commands</h2>
    <p>
      rsync is one of the most practical Linux tools for backups, deployments, and remote file transfers. It minimizes
      data transfer by copying only changed content, which makes it efficient for repeated synchronization jobs.
    </p>
    <p>
      If you are learning “how to use rsync”, start with clear source and destination paths plus archive mode.
      Then add targeted flags like compression, excludes, or deletion as your workflow becomes more predictable.
    </p>
    <p>
      Many incidents happen when <code>--delete</code> is used without testing. This is why dry-run support is important:
      it lets you inspect planned actions before modifying production files.
    </p>
    <p>
      This builder assembles the command for common Linux sync scenarios so you can move quickly while keeping commands
      explicit and reviewable for scripts, cron jobs, and operational runbooks.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card">
    <div class="grid">
      <label>Source path <input id="source" value="/srv/www/" /></label>
      <label>Destination path <input id="destination" value="backup@10.0.0.20:/data/www/" /></label>
      <label>Exclude pattern <input id="exclude" value="*.log" /></label>
    </div>
    <div class="checks">
      <label><input id="archive" type="checkbox" checked /> Archive (-a)</label>
      <label><input id="verbose" type="checkbox" checked /> Verbose (-v)</label>
      <label><input id="compress" type="checkbox" checked /> Compress (-z)</label>
      <label><input id="delete" type="checkbox" /> Delete removed files (--delete)</label>
      <label><input id="dryrun" type="checkbox" /> Dry run (--dry-run)</label>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="card">
    <h2>Generated command</h2>
    <pre id="rsync-output"></pre>
    <pre>Preview
rsync -a -v -z --dry-run --exclude='*.log' /srv/www/ backup@10.0.0.20:/data/www/</pre>
  </section>

  <script src="../../scripts/rsync-command-builder.ts"></script>
  <script is:inline type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)}></script>
  <style>
    .prose p { margin: 0.75rem 0; }
    .grid { display:grid; gap:.65rem; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit,minmax(230px,1fr)); }
    label { display:flex; gap:.45rem; align-items:center; }
    .grid label { display:grid; font-weight:600; gap:.35rem; }
    input { border:1px solid var(--border); background:var(--surface); color:var(--text); border-radius:.55rem; padding:.6rem .7rem; font:inherit; }
    .checks { display:grid; gap:.5rem; margin-top:.8rem; }
    pre { margin:0; background:var(--surface); border:1px solid var(--border); border-radius:.65rem; padding:.75rem; white-space:pre-wrap; }
  </style>
</BaseLayout>
